The '''Icelandic Centre for Research''' (RANNIS; Icelandic: Rannsóknamiðstöð Íslands) funds and promotes scientific research in [[Iceland]]. It formed in 2003 through an act of legislation.<ref>{{citation |title=Act on Public Support for Scientific Research No. 3/2003 |url=http://eng.menntamalaraduneyti.is/Acts/nr/2700 |year=2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070220072312/http://eng.menntamalaraduneyti.is/Acts/nr/2700 |archivedate= 20 February 2007 |deadurl=yes |publisher=Ministry of Education, Science and Culture |location= Reykjavik |work=Menntamalaraduneyti.is }}</ref><ref name=Andersen2007>{{citation |title=Foresight in the Nordic research and innovation council systems |author= Per Dannemand Andersen et al. |year=2007 |publisher=Risø National Laboratory |location=Denmark |isbn=978-87-550-3614-7 |url= http://orbit.dtu.dk/ws/files/7703099/ris_r_1613.pdf }}</ref> As of 2007, the [[Ministry of Education, Science and Culture (Iceland)|Ministry of Education, Science and Culture]] oversees its activities.<ref name=Andersen2007 /> It operates from headquarters on [[Borgartún]] in [[Reykjavík]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://en.rannis.is/activities/ |title= About Rannis |work=Rannis.is |publisher= Rannís |language=is, en |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>

==History==
From 1994 to 2003, the center operated as the Icelandic Research Council.<ref>{{citation |title=Research Councils in the Nordic Countries–Developments and Some Challenges |author=Hans Skoie |year= 2001 |url=http://hdl.handle.net/11250/274160 |publisher={{illm|Nordisk institutt for studier av innovasjon, forskning og utdanning|no}} (NIFU) }}</ref> "As of 2013 scientific publications based on projects, funded entirely or partially by the Icelandic Center for Research, Rannís, [[Open-access mandate|must be published]] in [[open access]]."<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.openaire.eu/oa-in-iceland |title=OA in Iceland |work=Open Access in Practice: EU Member States |publisher=[[OpenAIRE]] |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>

