{{about|the Dutch group|the Canadian group|Independent Senators Group}} {{Infobox political party | country = the Netherlands | colorcode = red |name = Independent Senate Group | native_name = Onafhankelijke Senaatsfractie |logo = Independent Senate Group NL logo.png |logo_size = 200px | leader = [[Henk ten Hoeve]] | chairman = [[Emma Kraak]] | leader1_title = Leader in the Senate | leader1_name = [[Henk ten Hoeve]] | leader2_title = Leader in the House of Representatives | leader2_name = | leader3_title = Leader in the European Parliament | leader3_name = | foundation = {{Start date|1995}} | merger = | split = | dissolved = | merged = | seats1_title = [[Senate of the Netherlands|Senate]] | seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|75|red}} | seats2_title = [[House of Representatives of the Netherlands|Seats in the House of Representatives]] | seats2 = | seats3_title = Seats in the European Parliament | seats3 = | ideology = [[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]] | position = [[Centre (politics)|Centre]]{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} | religion = | youth_wing = | wing1_title = Thinktank | wing1 = [[Stichting Ir. Marten Bierman]] | international = | european = | europarl = | colours = [[White]] and [[Red]] | headquarters = | website = {{URL|www.osf.nl}} }}
The '''Independent Senate Group''' ({{lang-nl|Onafhankelijke Senaatsfractie}}, OSF) is a [[parliamentary party]] in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] Senate with one senator, representing several provincial parties.
In 1995, several provincial parties and [[The Greens (Netherlands)|The Greens]] proposed their own list. [[Marten Bierman]] nominated by The Greens and second on the list was elected senator by a preference vote. In 1999, Bierman was re-elected. In 2003, [[Henk ten Hoeve]] became senator for the OSF. He had been member of the [[Fryslan|Friesland]] provincial legislature for the [[Frisian National Party]]. He remained senator and leader of the party until 2011, when his role was taken over by [[Kees de Lange]].
In 2015, Henk ten Hoeve became senator of the party for a second time.
The main parties involved are the Frisian National Party, the [[Party for the North]], the [[Party New Limburg]] and the [[Brabant Party]]. The Greens lost their provincial seats in 2003.
